# Day 14 – Sketch Constraints Challenge

## What I built
A challenge-based session focused entirely on applying all sketch constraints 
to fully define geometry without using dimensions. Completed the provided 
challenge file by locking each element using only constraints.

## Techniques used
- Applied all 12 sketch constraints: coincident, collinear, parallel, 
  perpendicular, equal, midpoint, tangent, smooth, symmetric, 
  horizontal/vertical, concentric, and fixed/grounded
- Distinguished when to use a constraint vs a dimension to lock geometry
- Identified under-constrained (blue) vs fully constrained (black) sketch lines
- Used the Sketch Palette to toggle constraint visibility

## Key rules learned
- Constraints define geometric relationships; dimensions define size — both 
  are needed to fully define a sketch
- Always aim for black lines before leaving a sketch; blue lines mean 
  degrees of freedom still exist
- Over-constraining (red lines) means conflicting rules — remove the 
  redundant constraint, not the dimension

## Time taken
~45 minutes

